'''Lucy Kasimwane''' is a business owner in the Solomon Islands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://europa.eu/capacity4dev/buildingresilience/blog/solomon-islands-farmers-meet-improve-cocoa-quality|title=Solomon Islands: Farmers meet to improve cocoa quality {{!}} capacity4dev.eu|website=europa.eu|language=en|access-date=2018-03-10}}</ref>

Kasimwane was born and raised in Ward 9 in the [[Makira-Ulawa Province]] of the Solomon Islands. She worked for the Australian government aid agency, [[AUSAID]], and later resigned to start her own business.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dfat.gov.au/about-us/publications/Documents/ausaid-annual-report-2011-12.pdf|title=AusAid Annual Report 2011-2012|last=Commonwealth of Australia|first=|date=2012|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=10 March 2018}}</ref> She is the owner of Lukasko Group, a private company involved in trading [[copra]] and wet cocoa beans.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://pacificwomeninbusiness.com.au/blog/snapshot/lucy-kasimwane-owner-lukasko-group-solomon-islands/|title=Lucy Kasimwane, Owner of Lukasko Group, Solomon Islands - Pacific Women in Business|work=Pacific Women in Business|access-date=2018-03-10|language=en-US}}</ref>

